    {
      "id": "line-003",
      "start": 12.2,
      "end": 15.2,
      "text": "This recording is by Mark Smith of Simpsonville, South Carolina.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-004",
      "start": 16.74,
      "end": 18.88,
      "text": "ESOP's Fables, the Prophet.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-005",
      "start": 21.04,
      "end": 25.78,
      "text": "A Prophet sat in the marketplace and told the fortunes of all who cared to engage his services.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-006",
      "start": 26.54,
      "end": 31.38,
      "text": "Suddenly there came running up one who told him that his house had been broken into by thieves,",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-007",
      "start": 32.12,
      "end": 34.72,
      "text": "and that they had made off with everything they could lay hands on.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-008",
      "start": 35.24,
      "end": 41.26,
      "text": "He was up in a moment and rushed off, tearing his hair and calling down curses on the miscreants.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-009",
      "start": 42.04,
      "end": 45.76,
      "text": "The bystanders were much amused, and one of them said,",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-010",
      "start": 45.76,
      "end": 49.54,
      "text": "Our friend professes to know what is going to happen to others,",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-011",
      "start": 50.26,
      "end": 54.56,
      "text": "but it seems he's not clever enough to perceive what's in store for himself.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-012",
      "start": 56.08,
      "end": 57.14,
      "text": "End of the Prophet.",
      "note": ""
    }
  ],
